{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180924192643|861043025","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Scott_Tipton","to":"Scott Tipton"}],"pages":{"4176183":{"pageid":4176183,"ns":0,"title":"Scott Tipton","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-24T19:28:58Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n|name         = Scott Tipton\n|image        = Scott Tipton official photo.jpg\n|state        = [[Colorado]]\n|district     = {{ushr|CO|3|3rd}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[John Salazar]]\n|successor    = \n|state_house1 = Colorado\n|district1    = 58th\n|term_start1  = January 9, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 2, 2011\n|predecessor1 = Ray Rose\n|successor1   = [[Don Coram]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|9}}\n|birth_place  = [[Espa\u00f1ola, New Mexico]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Jean Tipton\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Fort Lewis College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website      = {{url|tipton.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Scott R. Tipton''' (born November 9, 1956) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|CO|3}}. In November 2010, he defeated three-term [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[John Salazar]], to whom he lost by a wide margin in 2006. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He was previously a member of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]].\n\n==Early career==\nHe used to be a co-owner of a pottery company in [[Cortez, Colorado]].\n\nA lifelong Republican, he became involved in the unsuccessful [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1976|Reagan presidential campaign of 1976]] and was a delegate to the Republican Convention that year. He also assisted with local campaigns for Reagan in 1980 and 1984 across [[Montezuma County|Montezuma County, Colorado]] and the 3rd Congressional district and was Republican chairman of the 3rd Congressional district for eight years. He was a board member of [[Mesa Verde National Park]], [[Crow Canyon Archaeological Center]], and the advisory board of [[Pueblo Community College]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==Colorado legislature==\n\n===2008 election===\nOn February 5, 2008, he announced his candidacy for the Colorado House seat representing District 58. The announcement came shortly after the incumbent, Ray Rose, announced he would retire in 2008. He had no opposition in the Republican primary,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rs.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=syj1hm55hso5ty55pcuhyprg&ControlID=a61fb386-685c-4a0c-a691-71334ad539d8&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=ClientControllerdnn_ctr370_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&EnableFindNext=False&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 Primary Election |accessdate=2008-11-08 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but faced Democratic candidate Noelle Hagan in the November 2008 general election. Hagan's candidacy was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]''<ref>{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=October 17, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}</ref> and the ''Montrose Daily Press.''<ref>{{cite news |first=Wendy |last=Norris |author2=Bob Spencer  |title=State candidate endorsement watch |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/11911/state-candidate-endorsement-watch |work=Colorado Independent |date=November 3, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}</ref> Tipton won the election with 59 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWith Representatives [[Laura Bradford]] and [[Frank McNulty (Colorado legislator)|Frank McNulty]], Tipton planned on re-introducing a version of [[Jessica's Law]] to establish minimum sentences for [[child sex offender]]s,<ref>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Jessica's Law bill gets state sponsors |url=http://www.postindependent.com/article/20081125/COMMUNITY_NEWS/811249962 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=November 24, 2008 |accessdate=January 27, 2014 }}</ref> sponsoring bills to create a full-time judge position in [[Montrose, Colorado|Montrose]]<ref>{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Rep. Tipton's issues include roads, sexual assault, education |url=http://www.cortezjournal.com/Main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=3813 |work=Cortez Journal |date=December 24, 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728120701/http://www.cortezjournal.com/Main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=3813 |archivedate=July 28, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=Budget Woes Will Handcuff Colorado Legislature |url=http://www.telluridewatch.com/pages/full_story?page_label=news&id=1253738-Budget-Woes-Will-Handcuff-Colorado-Legislature&widget=push&instance=secondary_stories_left_column&article-Budget-Woes-Will-Handcuff-Colorado-Legislature%20=&open=& |work=Telluride Watch |date=January 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-10 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and to simplify water rights filing.<ref>{{cite news |first=Reilly |last=Capps |title=Ahern may give it another go |url=http://www.telluridenews.com/articles/2009/01/12/news/doc496be8bcf23ab611488556.txt |work=Telluride Daily Planet |date=January 12, 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-04 }}</ref> The attempt to introduce a version of Jessica's Law was unsuccessful, it dying in committee.<ref>{{cite news |first=Reilly |last=Capps |title=Political accusations fly after Colorado's \"Jessica's Law\" dies|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_22670788/political-accusations-fly-after-colorados-jessicas-law-dies |work=Telluride The Denver Post |date=February 26, 2009 |accessdate=January 27, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Tipton was named to seats on the House Agriculture, Livestock, and Natural Resources Committee and the House Local Government Committee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=November 18, 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Scott Tipton, Official Portrait, 112th Congress.JPG|thumb|Tipton's 112th Congress session photo]]\n\n===Elections===\n;2006\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2006#District 3}}\nHe unsuccessfully challenged the first term [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] U.S. congressman, [[John Salazar]]. Tipton lost 38% to 62% for Salazar.<ref>{{cite news | first = Gary | last = Harmon | title = Salazar-Tipton rematch a different contest | date = 2010-08-03 | url = http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/salazartipson_rematch_a_differ | work = [[Grand Junction Daily Sentinel]] | accessdate = 2010-10-28}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2010#District 3}}\nIn the Republican primary, he defeated Bob McConnell 56% to 44%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2010/aug/10/tough-loss-steamboats-bob-mcconnell/|title=Steamboat's McConnell defeated in District 3, Scott Tipton wins GOP congressional primary, goes on to face Rep. John Salazar|last=Lawrence|first=Mike|date=2010-08-10|work=[[Steamboat Pilot & Today|Steamboat Pilot]]|quote=With 70 percent of precincts reporting results Tuesday night, Tipton, a state representative from Cortez, had received 56 percent of votes across the 3rd Congressional District, compared with about 44 percent for McConnell.|accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref> He again challenged [[John Salazar|Salazar]] in {{ushr|CO|3}}. [[Libertarian Party (US)|Libertarian]] Gregory Gilman and independent Jake Segrest were also on the ballot, with independents John W. Hargis, Sr. and James Fritz qualified as write-in candidates. He decided to retire from the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] to run for Congress in 2010, again challenging Salazar.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rollcall.com/news/40479-1.html?type=printer_friendly | title = Tipton Joins Race Against Salazar | author = Greg Giroux | publisher = Roll Call | date = 2009-11-09 | accessdate = 2009-11-25}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Salazar 50.10% to 45.76%.\n\n;2012\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2012#District 3}}\nIn 2012, he was challenged by [[Sal Pace]], a [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] state representative from [[Pueblo, Colorado|Pueblo]]. His re-election campaign was aided by $1.3 million in advertising against Pace, funded by the [[Grover Norquist]] led, [[Americans for Tax Reform]].<ref>{{cite news|title=ATR Announces 1.3 Million Dollar Ad Buy in Colorado's 3rd Congressional District|url=http://www.atr.org/atr-announces-point-million-dollar-ad-a7247|accessdate=October 30, 2012|date=October 12, 2012}}</ref> SG Interests, an oil and gas company from Texas, that sought to drill in the Thompson Divide area, also campaigned against Pace.<ref>{{cite news|title=Driller starts super PAC to support Tipton|url=http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029486/Driller-starts-super-PAC-to-support-Tipton--|accessdate=October 30, 2012|date=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2014#District 3}}\nIn 2014, he was challenged by Democrat Abel Tapia, Libertarian Travis Mero and UNA candidate Tisha Cadia.  He won with 56.14% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado Secretary of State|url=http://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Results/Abstract/2014/general/congress.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n\nTipton voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> According to Tipton, the bill fixes a \"broken tax code\" and \"puts the needs of the American people before special interests.\"<ref name=\"Northrop122017\">{{cite web|last1=Northrop|first1=Samuel|title=Colorado Republicans tout tax plan headed to president's desk|url=https://durangoherald.com/articles/200469-colorado-republicans-tout-tax-plan-headed-to-presidents-desk|website=Durango Herald|accessdate=22 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> Tipton touts that the act \"supports families, graduate students, homeowners, and small businesses,\" and is \"a victory for Coloradans and all Americans.\"<ref name=\"Matthews122017\">{{cite web|last1=Matthews|first1=Mark|title=How Colorado lawmakers voted on the federal tax overhaul \u2014 and why|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2017/12/20/colorado-lawmakers-tax-vote/|website=The Denver Post|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands|Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]], chairman\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations|Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n'''Caucus Memberships'''\n*Congressional Cement Caucus\n*[[Congressional Gaming Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n===2016 presidential election===\nTipton expressed support for then-candidate [[Donald Trump]] in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.9news.com/news/politics/would-colorado-gop-officials-back-trump/72471618|title=Would Colorado GOP officials back Trump?|last=TEGNA|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en-US|newspaper=KUSA}}</ref> After the [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape]] was released, in which Trump and [[Billy Bush]] had a lewd exchange about women, Tipton did not rescind his endorsement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://durangoherald.com/articles/109765-scott-tipton-j-paul-brown-stick-with-donald-trump|title=Scott Tipton, J. Paul Brown stick with Donald Trump|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en|newspaper=durangoherald.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic issues ===\nTipton has said, \"we have a problem with reckless spending across the board at the federal level.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> He has signed [[Grover Norquist]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]],<ref name=\"ATR\">{{cite web|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> and a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Tipton_Scott.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614201944/http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Tipton_Scott.pdf |archivedate=June 14, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He has also supported the [[The Path to Prosperity|Ryan Plan]], having twice voted for it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chieftain.com/news/local/tipton-defends-gop-approach/article_4a4ef9e0-6266-11e0-bbbd-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Tipton defends GOP approach|date=2011-04-09|publisher=Pueblo Chieftain|author=Peter Roper|accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, he voted against a resolution that would have directed the House to request 10 years of Trump's tax returns, which would then have been reviewed by the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] in a closed session.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indy100.com/article/republican-vote-donald-trump-tax-president-united-states-229-185-congress-7603851|title=These are all the Republicans who don't want you to see Donald Trump's tax returns|date=2017-02-28|work=indy100|access-date=2017-03-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nTipton rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/gop-rep-tipton-wont-acknowledge-human-caused-climate-change-because-it-would-divide-america-760f4b00100a|title=GOP Rep Tipton Won't Acknowledge Human-Caused Climate Change Because It Would 'Divide America'|last=ThinkProgress|date=2012-08-23|website=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref> He argues that climate change is driven by natural climate cycles.<ref name=\":3\" /> He opposes the [[Paris Agreement]], the international agreement which mitigates greenhouse gas emissions.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHe opposes federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has a 8% score by the League of Conservation Voters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/scott-tipton|title=Check out Representative Scott Tipton's Environmental Voting Record|newspaper=League of Conservation Voters Scorecard|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, while serving in the state legislature, Tipton voted against legislation to compel [[Xcel Energy]] to convert three [[coal power plant]]s to [[natural gas]] power plants. He also voted against legislation to [[Renewable portfolio standard|require electricity utilities to use more renewable energy]].<ref>Mark K. Matthews, [http://www.denverpost.com/2016/09/12/lost-coal-jobs-fuel-debate-gail-schwartz-scott-tipton-race/ Lost coal jobs fuel debate in Gail Schwartz-Scott Tipton race on Western Slope], ''Denver Post'' (September 12, 2016).</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Tipton wrote a draft bill on oil and gas drilling in the Thompson Divide that contained large sections taken \"word for word\" from a proposal offered by a SG Interests, a Texas-based energy company and its lobbying firm. Tipton's draft legislation (which he described as a \"starting point\") was criticized because of Tipton's receipt of $39,000 in campaign contributions from SG Interests over the course of his career.<ref>Mark K. Matthews, [http://www.denverpost.com/2016/04/29/tipton-proposal-largely-written-by-oil-and-gas-company-draws-criticism/ Tipton proposal, largely written by oil and gas company, draws criticism], ''Denver Post'' (April 29, 2016).</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Tipton voted in favor of legislation that would make it easier to sell federal public lands. Tipton came under criticism from conservation groups for his vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://durangoherald.com/articles/126094-rep-scott-tipton-vote-spurs-ire-from-public-land-supporters|title=Rep. Scott Tipton vote spurs ire from public land supporters|newspaper=durangoherald.com|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Water rights ====\nTipton introduced the [[Water Rights Protection Act]] into the House on September 26, 2013. The bill would prevent federal agencies from requiring certain entities to relinquish their water rights to the United States in order to use [[public lands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44956|title=H.R. 3189 - CBO|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> Tipton said the bill was needed because it \"provides critical protection for water rights' holders from federal takings by ensuring that federal government agencies cannot extort private property rights through uneven-handed negotiations.\"<ref name=\"COtiptonbill\">{{cite news|url=http://thecoloradoobserver.com/2013/10/tipton-bill-seeks-to-stop-feds-from-trampling-water-rights/|title=Tipton Bill Seeks to Stop Feds from Trampling Water Rights|last=Hudson|first=Audrey|date=October 11, 2013|newspaper=The Colorado Observer|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref> Tipton argued that the bill \"prohibits federal agencies from pilfering water rights through the use of permits, leases, and other land management arrangements, for which it would otherwise have to pay just compensation under the 5th Amendment of the Constitution.\"<ref name=\"COtiptonbill\" />\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\nHe has criticized the Obama administration for inaction in the Middle East: \"President Obama and Secretary Clinton's inaction in the Middle East has emboldened Syria, Iran and Russia and led to the death and displacement of millions of Syrian civilians.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nHe is in favor of repealing the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\":0\" /> On May 4, 2017, he voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/04/health-care-vote-puts-pressure-dozens-vulnerable-gop-reps/101297824/|title=Health care vote puts pressure on dozens of vulnerable GOP reps|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT issues ===\nHe opposes same-sex marriage.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has voted in favor of provisions which would allow federal contractors to discriminate against people based on their sexual orientation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whatthefolly.com/2016/05/23/list-of-213-republican-members-of-the-house-who-voted-to-allow-federal-contractors-to-discriminate-against-lgbt-workers/|title=List of 213 Republican members of the House who voted to allow federal contractors to discriminate against LGBT workers {{!}} What The Folly?!|access-date=2017-02-13|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214004255/http://www.whatthefolly.com/2016/05/23/list-of-213-republican-members-of-the-house-who-voted-to-allow-federal-contractors-to-discriminate-against-lgbt-workers/|archivedate=February 14, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=May 2018}}\n\n=== Immigration and refugees ===\nTipton has said, \"I strongly oppose amnesty or any special benefits for illegal immigrants\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rockymountainpost.com/schwartz-decries-tipton-immigration-stance-linking-extreme-views-trump/|title=Schwartz decries Tipton immigration stance, linking 'extreme' views to Trump - Rocky Mountain Post|date=2016-10-28|newspaper=Rocky Mountain Post|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> He criticized President Obama for his executive order allowing up to five million illegal immigrants \"to come out of the shadows\" and work openly in the country.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nTipton takes a \"hardline stance\" on the [[refugees of the Syrian Civil War]] and opposes the admission of Syrian refugees to the United States.<ref name=\"Matthews\">Mark Matthews, [http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2015/11/18/scott-tipton-takes-hardline-stance-on-syria-raises-profile/123869/ Scott Tipton takes hardline stance on Syria, raises profile], ''Denver Post'' (November 18, 2015).</ref> He has clashed with Governor [[John Hickenlooper]] about the resettlement of refugee families in Colorado.<ref name=\"Matthews\"/>\n\n=== Abortion===\nHe opposes abortion.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/65403/scott-tipton/#.WKHckBKLSfQ|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Project Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cpr.org/news/story/colorado-congressional-district-3-race-tipton-schwartz-and-kent-on-the-issues|title=Colorado Congressional District 3 Race: Tipton, Schwartz And Kent On The Issues|last=Sakas|first=Michael|newspaper=Colorado Public Radio|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n{{POV section|date=May 2018}}\nIn 2011, it was reported that he spent over $7,000 on vendors that did business with his nephew's company.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/colo-rep-tipton-facing-second-ethics-issue | title = Colo. Rep. Tipton Facing Second Ethics Issue | publisher = TheDenverChannel.com | date = 2011-06-09 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref> Also in 2011, Tipton wrote an apology letter to the [[House Ethics Committee]] after it became known that his daughter was using his name in an effort to secure government contracts from other Congressional offices.  In 2012, he violated House rules when his office mistakenly used taxpayer resources to promote a campaign event.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_20084097 | title = Rep. Tipton violates House rules in promoting campaign event | author = Allison Sherry | publisher = The Denver Post | date = 2012-03-02 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\nA [[super PAC]], funded by oil and gas driller SG Interests, is registered at the address of Tipton's campaign attorney and run by a law clerk in his office.  Tipton's attorney said: \"I have specifically put up Chinese walls to make sure Charlie (law clerk) is in no way involved with the Tipton campaign, and I'm in no way involved with the Colorado Future Fund.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029486/Driller-starts-super-PAC-to-support-Tipton-- | title = Driller starts super PAC to support Tipton | publisher = Durango Herald | date = 2012-10-29 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://tipton.house.gov/ Congressman Scott Tipton] official U.S. House site\n* [http://votetipton.com/ Scott Tipton for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Colorado/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Scott_Tipton_%5BR-3%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|scotttipton}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=T000470 | votesmart=65403 | fec=H6CO03139 | congress=scott-tipton/1997 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Salazar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Colorado|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Colorado's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Stivers]]<br>R-[[Ohio]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=233rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Daniel Webster (Florida politician)|Daniel Webster]]<br>R-[[Florida]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CO-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{ColoradoUSRepresentatives}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tipton, Scott}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:Fort Lewis College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Cortez, Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Espa\u00f1ola, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People from Montrose, Colorado]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]"}]}}}}